<section xml:id="section-activity-clo11">
  <title>Activity for CLO-11</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo11-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are secant and tangent lines?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          On the graph of a function, a secant line is a line that
          goes through two different points on the graph of the
          funciton. A tangent line is a line that just touches the
          graph of a function at one point while not crossing it. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How is a tangent line approximated by secant lines?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A secont line has two points on the graph. Fix one of the
          points, and let the second point get closer and closer to
          the first point. This produces a sequence of secant lines
          which are getting closer and closer to the tangent lines.
          These are approximations to the tangent lines, and the
          closer the second point, the better the approximation. In
          the limit of this process, the tangent line itself can be
          produces. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the geometric interpretation of a derivative.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A derivative is the slope of a tangent line to the graph of
          a function. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How is the derivative defined. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For points <m>x</m> and <m>a</m> in the domain of the
          function, the slope of the secont line is given by this
          <sq>rise over run</sq> expression.
          <md>
            \frac{f(x) - f(a)}{x - a}
          </md>
          Since the derivative is the limit of the slope of the secant
          line as the points get closer, I defined by derivative as a
          limit. 
          <md>
            f^\prime(a) = \lim_{x \rightarrow a} \frac{f(x) - f(a)}{x
            - a}
          </md>
          There are adjustment to this definition. The most common
          definition let <m>h</m> be the difference between the two
          inputs, which leads to the following limit. 
          <md>
            f^\prime(x) = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{f(x+ h) -
            f(x)}{h}
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a differential operator?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A differential operator is a mathematical symbol that
          indicates <sq>take a derivative</sq>. In Leibniz notation,
          the denominator indicates the independent variable.
          Therefore, these are all differential operators in different
          independent variables. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \frac{d}{dx} \amp \amp \frac{d}{dt} \amp \amp
              \frac{d}{ds}
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a differentiable function?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A differentiable function is a function where the derivative
          exists: that is, the limit that defines the derivative is a
          convergent limit. It is a function that has a well-defined
          tangent line (and slope) at each point in its domain.
          Visually, it is a function that is continuous and has no
          sharp corners in its graph. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-derivative-definition">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Derivatives by Definition</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate this derivative by definition.
          <md>
            \frac{d}{dx} (x^2-4)
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I use the limit definition of the derivative.
          <md>
            \frac{d}{dx} (x^2-4) = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}
            \frac{(x+h)^2 - 4 - (x^2-4)}{h} 
          </md>
          Then I simplify this expression, trying to find a way to
          factor an <m>h</m> from the numerator so that I can cancel
          it with the <m>h</m> from the denominator. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{(x+h)^2 - 4 - (x^2-4)}{h}
              \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{x^2 + 2xh + h^2 - 4 -
              x^2 + 4}{h} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{2xh + h^2}{h} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{h(2x + h)}{h} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} 2x + h  = 2x+0 = 2x
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Therefore, the derivative is <m>2x</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate this derivative by definition.
          <md>
            \frac{d}{dx} \sqrt{5x}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I use the limit definition of the derivative.
          <md>
            \frac{d}{dx} \sqrt{5x} = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}
            \frac{\sqrt{5(x+h)} - \sqrt{5x}}{h} 
          </md>
          Then I simplify this expression, trying to find a way to
          factor an <m>h</m> from the numerator so that I can cancel
          it with the <m>h</m> from the denominator. I use a trick
          here called multiplying by the conjugate. This trick will
          remove the square roots from the numerator (it also makes
          the denominator more complicated, but that's not a problem).
          This trick is based on the idea that if I multiply the top
          and bottom of a fraction by the same thing, then I haven't
          changed the value of the fraction at all. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sqrt{5(x+h)} - \sqrt{5x}}{h}
              \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{(\sqrt{5(x+h)} -
              \sqrt{5x})(\sqrt{5(x+h)} + \sqrt{5x})}{h(\sqrt{5(x+h)} +
              \sqrt{5x})}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{5(x+h) -
              5x}{h(\sqrt{5(x+h)} + \sqrt{5x})} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{5x + 5h -
              5x}{h(\sqrt{5(x+h)} + \sqrt{5x})} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{5h}{h(\sqrt{5(x+h)}
              + \sqrt{5x})} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{5}{(\sqrt{5(x+h)}
              + \sqrt{5x})} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          After multiplying by the conjugate, simplifying the
          numerator, and cancelling the <m>h</m> from numerator and
          denominator, I reach a point where I can simply evaluate
          the limit by replacing <m>h</m> with 0. 
          <md>
           \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{5}{(\sqrt{5(x+h)}
            + \sqrt{5x})} = \frac{5}{\sqrt{5x}+ \sqrt{5x}} =
            \frac{5}{2\sqrt{5x}} 
          </md>
          This is a reasonable expression for the derivative of the
          original function. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
